(listOfParasInChapter Ball-Sound-Original
                      (TheList
                       (SourceTextChapterParagraphFn Ball-Sound-Original 1 1)))

(textContentsOfSourceText-Canonical 
 (SourceTextChapterParagraphFn Ball-Sound-Original 1 1)
 "A ball is thrown at a sidewalk.
When the ball hits the sidewalk, the ball bounces back.
The ball is thrown at a pillow.
When the ball hits the pillow, the ball stops.
A sound is like the ball.
When the sound hits a hard surface, it bounces back.
When the sound hits a soft surface, the sound stops.")


(listOfParasInChapter Gold-Mine-Solar-Original
                      (TheList
                       (SourceTextChapterParagraphFn Gold-Mine-Solar-Original 1 1)))

(textContentsOfSourceText-Canonical 
 (SourceTextChapterParagraphFn Gold-Mine-Solar-Original 1 1)
 "A man owns a mine.
A gold mine contains poor ore.
Mining gold requires digging much.
Processing the ore requires expensive mining equipment.
Acquiring the gold requires processing the ore.
The gold is free, but acquiring the gold is expensive.
Acquiring the gold benefits the man, if a monetary value of the gold rises.
Acquiring the gold benefits the man, if a monetary value of the mining equipment falls.
Acquiring the gold harms the man, if the monetary value of the gold falls.
Acquiring the gold harms the man, if the monetary value of the mining equipment rises.
A gold mine in Utah closes, if the monetary value of the gold falls.
The gold mine opens, if the monetary value of the gold rises.
Solar radiation is like the poor ore.
Acquiring solar energy requires collecting the solar radiation.
Using the solar energy requires transforming the solar energy into electricity.
The solar collector collects the solar energy.
Similarly, the mining equipment collects the gold.
The solar collector is expensive.
The solar collector is more expensive than the solar radiation.
The solar heating system saves cash, if a monetary value of the electricity rises.
The solar heating system wastes cash, if the monetary value of the electricity falls. 
The gold mine in Utah closes, if the gold mine wastes cash.
Similarly, if the monetary value of the electricity falls, a solar heating system in Florida closes.
Because the monetary value of gold now rises, the gold mine in Utah makes cash.
Similarly, the monetary value of the electricity now rises.
Because the monetary value of the electricity rises, the solar heating system saves cash. 
The solar collector collects sunlight.
The solar collector is like the mining equipment.
Mining the poor ore wastes cash, if the monetary value of the mining equipment falls.
The mining equipment possesses longevity, if the mining equipment possesses simplicity. 
Similarly, if the solar collector possesses simplicity, the solar collector possesses longevity. 
Because the flat plate system possesses simplicity, the flat plate system saves cash.")


(listOfParasInChapter Bucket-Brick-Original
                      (TheList
                       (SourceTextChapterParagraphFn Bucket-Brick-Original 1 1)))

(textContentsOfSourceText-Canonical 
 (SourceTextChapterParagraphFn Bucket-Brick-Original 1 1)
 "A hot brick leaks heat to a cool room.
The temperature difference between the brick's temperature and the room's temperature pushes the heat from the brick. 
The heat escapes until the temperature difference disappears.
The hot brick is like a bucket of the water.
There is a hole in the bucket.
The water exits the bucket through the hole.
The water's depth exceeds the hole's height.
The water flows from the bucket.
The depth difference between the water's depth and the hole's height causes the exit.
After the water leaves, the depth difference disappears. 
When the depth difference disappears, the exit stops.
The temperature difference is like the depth difference. ")



(listOfParasInChapter Water-Storage-Heat-Storage-Original
                      (TheList
                       (SourceTextChapterParagraphFn Water-Storage-Heat-Storage-Original 1 1)))

(textContentsOfSourceText-Canonical 
 (SourceTextChapterParagraphFn Water-Storage-Heat-Storage-Original 1 1)
 "The brick in the room stores heat.
The bucket stores a volume of the water.
Storing the heat is like storing the volume.
The volume of the water that the bucket stores depends on the depth of the water.
Similarly, the heat that the brick stores depends on the temperature of the brick.
A solar heating system heats a house, if the heat is stored at a high temperature.
The heat is useful, if a material's temperature is higher than the room's temperature.
The value of the volume of the water in the bucket rises, if the volume of the water reaches above the valve.
If the volume of the water falls below the valve, the value of the volume of the water falls.
The heat that the brick stores depends on a quantity of the brick.
If the brick's quantity increases, the brick stores much heat.
If the bucket's size increases, the bucket stores much water.
If the size of the bucket decreases, the bucket stores little water.")

