The bucket stores a volume of the water.
Storing the heat is like storing the volume.
The volume of the water that the bucket stores depends on the depth of the water.")

(listOfParasInChapter Phase-Change-Materials-Original
                      (TheList
                       (SourceTextChapterParagraphFn Phase-Change-Materials-Original 1 1)))

(textContentsOfSourceText-Canonical 
 (SourceTextChapterParagraphFn Phase-Change-Materials-Original 1 1)
 "Wax is a phase change material.
The wax is like a bucket of liquid with a bump.
The bottom of the bucket is below the bump of the bucket.
Adding the liquid to the bottom quickly increases the liquid's depth.
Adding the liquid to the bump slowly increases the depth of the liquid.
The bump stores the liquid.
The wax stores the heat, when the wax melts.
The wax stores the heat like the bump stores the liquid.
If the bucket drains, the liquid is recovered.
If the wax freezes, the heat is recovered.
If the depth lies at the bump, removing the liquid slowly decreases the depth.
Near the wax's melting point, removing the heat slowly changes the temperature of the wax.")


(listOfParasInChapter Faucet-Furnace-Original
                      (TheList
                       (SourceTextChapterParagraphFn Faucet-Furnace-Original 1 1)))

(textContentsOfSourceText-Canonical 
 (SourceTextChapterParagraphFn Faucet-Furnace-Original 1 1)
 "The temperature of a house is like the depth of the water in a bucket.
Heat is like the water.
A flow of the heat is like a flow of the water.
The water flows into the bucket from a faucet.
The bucket has a hole.
The furnace of the house is like the faucet.
The faucet pumps the water into the bucket.
Similarly, the furnace pumps the heat into the house.
The water exits the bucket through the hole in the bucket.
Similarly, the heat exits the house through the wall of the house.
The temperature of the house is like the depth of the water in a bucket.
A distance between the temperature of the house and the outside's temperature pushes heat from the house. 
A distance between the depth of the water and the bucket's bottom pushes water from the bucket. 
The temperature of the outside is like the bottom of the bucket.
A thermostat maintains the temperature of the house.
A line on the bucket marks the depth of the target.
If the depth of the water falls below the line, the faucet adds the water.
Similarly, if the temperature of the house falls below the thermostat, the furnace adds the heat.")

(listOfParasInChapter Faucet-Furnace-Original-mini
                      (TheList
                       (SourceTextChapterParagraphFn Faucet-Furnace-Original-mini 1 1)))

(textContentsOfSourceText-Canonical 
 (SourceTextChapterParagraphFn Faucet-Furnace-Original-mini 1 1)
 "The temperature of a house is like the depth of the water in a bucket.
The water flows into the bucket from a faucet.
The bucket has a hole.")


(listOfParasInChapter Leak-Insulation-Original-Old
                      (TheList
                       (SourceTextChapterParagraphFn Leak-Insulation-Original 1 1)))

(textContentsOfSourceText-Canonical 
 (SourceTextChapterParagraphFn Leak-Insulation-Original-Old 1 1)
 "Heat leaves a house through a wall.
The wall is like a hole in a bucket.
Insulation for the house is like a reduction of the size of the hole.
A reduction of leakage results from the reduction of the size of the hole.
It reduces the water added by the faucet.
Similarly, the furnace infrequently adds the heat to the house with insulation.
The water that the faucet adds balances the leakage.
Similarly, the heat that the furnace adds balances the leave of the heat.")

(listOfParasInChapter Leak-Insulation-Original
                      (TheList
                       (SourceTextChapterParagraphFn Leak-Insulation-Original 1 1)))

(textContentsOfSourceText-Canonical 
 (SourceTextChapterParagraphFn Leak-Insulation-Original 1 1)
 "Remember: A house is like a bucket with holes in the bottom.
The heat lost through the walls is like the water lost through the holes.
Insulating a house is like reducing the size of the holes in the bucket.
Reducing the size of the holes reduces the volume of lost water.
Reducing the volume of lost water reduces the volume of water we have to add.
The furnace is like the faucet.
The faucet needs to pump less water if the volume of lost water is reduced.
The furnace needs to pump less heat if the amount of lost heat is reduced.")




(listOfParasInChapter Rain-Sunlight-Original
                      (TheList
                       (SourceTextChapterParagraphFn Rain-Sunlight-Original 1 1)))

(textContentsOfSourceText-Canonical 
 (SourceTextChapterParagraphFn Rain-Sunlight-Original 1 1)
 "A bucket is in a rain storm.
A solar collector is like the bucket.
The bucket collects rain; the solar collector collects sunlight.
Collecting the rainwater requires angling the bucket towards the rain.
An open top of the bucket collects the rain. The top points towards the rain. 
If the rain falls straight down, the top lies flat.
If wind blows the rain, the top angles toward the rain. 
Similarly, collecting the sunlight requires pointing the solar collector towards the sunlight.")

(listOfParasInChapter Stagnation-Stagnation-Original
                      (TheList
                       (SourceTextChapterParagraphFn Stagnation-Stagnation-Original 1 1)))

(textContentsOfSourceText-Canonical 
 (SourceTextChapterParagraphFn Stagnation-Stagnation-Original 1 1)
 "A solar panel is like a rain collection system.
The solar panel collects solar radiation.
The rain collection system catches rainwater with a tray.
A pipe attaches to the tray.
However, the pipe has a leak.
The water leaks quickly, as the pipe fills.
The spillage balances the intake, when the pipe fills.
When the spillage balances the intake, the water stops rising.
When the spillage balances the intake, the water reaches a stagnation depth.
A stagnation temperature is like the stagnation depth.
A solar cell attaches to the solar panel.
When the heat's leakage balances the incoming solar radiation,
the heat in the solar panel reaches a stagnation temperature.")


(listOfParasInChapter Intensity-Rain-Sunlight-Original
                      (TheList
                       (SourceTextChapterParagraphFn Intensity-Rain-Sunlight-Original 1 1)))

(textContentsOfSourceText-Canonical 
 (SourceTextChapterParagraphFn Intensity-Rain-Sunlight-Original 1 1)
 "A solar collector is like a rain collection system.
A drizzle falls on the rain collection system's tray.
Little solar radiation hits the solar collector.
The little solar radiation is like the drizzle.
Because the drizzle falls, the tray collects little water.
Because the drizzle falls, the intake is reduced.
If the water's depth falls, the spillage is reduced.
If the depth of the water rises, the spillage is increased.
If the intake is reduced, a low depth pushes the intake from the pipe.
If the intake is reduced, the stagnation depth is reduced.
If the intake is reduced, the low depth balances the intake.
If the solar radiation is reduced, the stagnation temperature is reduced.")

(listOfParasInChapter Atmosphere-Greenhouse-Original
                      (TheList
                       (SourceTextChapterParagraphFn Atmosphere-Greenhouse-Original 1 1)))

(textContentsOfSourceText-Canonical 
 (SourceTextChapterParagraphFn Atmosphere-Greenhouse-Original 1 1)
 "A greenhouse gas is a gas.
The greenhouse effect occurs, when a greenhouse gas warms stuff. 
The greenhouse gas's name comes from a greenhouse. 
The greenhouse effect's name comes from a greenhouse. 
The glass composes a greenhouse. 
The greenhouse gas is like the glass.
The greenhouse gas in the atmosphere admits sunlight.
The glass of the greenhouse admits sunlight.
The greenhouse gas traps heat.
The glass traps heat. 
Vegetation in the greenhouse grows despite the winter.
The winter is cold outside the greenhouse. 
Similarly, life thrives in the atmosphere despite the environment.
The environment outside the atmosphere is harsh.")



